\f2 	One summer I drove up the pine-lined coast of Vancouver Island in British Columbia. I didn\'92t have any particular destination in mind. The prospect of Tofino had occurred to me, but that would be several hours further along the coast. The region, what Americans refer to as the Pacific Northwest, is somewhat lesser known in the American imaginary. To describe the landscape briefly, it is a place where mountains and large coniferous forests directly meet the Pacific ocean. The beaches of this place are also comparatively alien, particularly to someone who has spent their life in the east, where fine sand beaches are more common. In the northwest, one finds rocky beaches composed of small to medium sized stones. The colors are extraordinary. Amid the giant sea stacks and escarpments, the foamy surf of the water washes up and recedes upon these stones that glisten in pinks, greens, oranges, blues, and purples \'96 products of volcanism, water, wind, and time. Even the more common basalt grey ones shine under a typical cloudy day. The summer time however brings long spells of sunshine. I stopped my car at a small, nameless beach park where only a few travelers or area residents were sitting and begin to hike toward one of the bordering escarpments where a giant pine was perched. The erosion had exposed some of its finer roots the saltwater and air. I clambered over the boulders at the base of this outcropping, as best as a non-native could. These types of giant rocks, immediately adjacent to the place where water greets the land, are notorious for their danger, covered in slick seaweed, anemones and razor-sharp, black mussels. Further along and closer to the escarpment, I entered a small cave \'96 really more of an arbor considering the tree\'92s roots jutted down from overhead. This was a calm place, sequestered away from even the scant amount of people a few dozen yards away. The cave cut underneath the escarpment and continued around away from the beach. To my surprise, I found the path led upward through the soil and to the small, grass and moss covered area around the tree. From this vantage, I saw the boulders below, the stone beach, the people, but now even more: the coastline leading northward, oceangoing vessels, more pine-covered islands and mountains in the far distance.\
	These kinds of perspectives \'96 on the beach, over top the boulders, inside the cave, above on the tree\'92s perch \'96 all inform an experience of what would be considered the world outside our interior spaces \'96 our homes, office buildings, and the rooms and spaces inside them. As we venture into more metaphorical (and metaphysical) spaces provided by computers, the contrast with the exterior space has been extended, one step further removed from such a wild, if serene scene. The computer itself acts a technological extension of our mind\'92s interiority. The subsequent virtual spaces on it reflect as such (desktops, windows, bins, folders, file systems, and on).  But the metaphors we use to move in and comprehend any of these spaces turn out to be universal. Grasping to understand a concept within a virtual, interior, or exterior space follows a similar heuristic:\
